	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f97803542718286><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=97803542718286>RE: Trade skills</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=97803542718286#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=4986><span id=Scholar>Alerithon</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>92 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Dec 28th 8:31 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Two trains of thought.&nbsp;&nbsp;One, as in the other posts, tailoring (and by relation, brewing) are more practical for the monk.  You get to make your own armor, and around skill level 50, you can make hand made backpacks, which can be very profitable.  You also now get the bearskin potion bag, trivial I think around 60 or 70.  Not as wide a market, but still a money maker.  If you master brewing, you might get some custom making tempers.<br><br>If you're human, though, you might want to think about smithing.  If you make any of the the leathers (studded/reinforced, very small market) you'll need a smith.  The human master smith gets 2 sets of racial recipies, one for Freeport, one for Qeynos.  And as a monk, you're higher str and dex might help you with success rates/skilling up in smithing.  Plus smithing is a more reliable source of income over hunting for the elusive HQ bear pelt.<br>&nbsp;<br>Alerithon Tigerspirit<br>29 rank monk, E'Ci<br>Avatara</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
